{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cb940e2d-5f13-4787-92cb-362c26a8ae3d","content":"In .NET MAUI, the app lifecycle moved from `Application` to the `Window` class. Create a custom `Window` subclass and override the corresponding methods:\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()    // replaces OnStart\n    {\n        base.OnCreated();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnStopped()    // replaces OnSleep\n    {\n        base.OnStopped();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnResumed()    // replaces OnResume\n    {\n        base.OnResumed();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThen in your `App` class, override `CreateWindow`:\n\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        return new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Quick mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart` | `OnCreated` |\n| `OnSleep` | `OnStopped` |\n| `OnResume` | `OnResumed` |\n\nThere's also `OnActivated`/`OnDeactivated` for finer-grained focus tracking, and `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` for platform-specific hooks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1b70a8f9-4f88-4b43-9671-037552f6c58c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a straightforward knowledge question about the MAUI lifecycle API.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` class. In .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You now use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events through the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can override `CreateWindow` and hook into `Window` events.\n\nActually, let me be more precise:\n\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the `Application` class no longer has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` methods. Instead, lifecycle management moved to the `Window` class, where you can override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and subscribe to window events like `Created`, `Resumed`, and `Stopped`, or create a custom `Window` subclass with its own lifecycle overrides. So the `Window` class lifecycle methods map directly from the old `Application` lifecycle—`OnCreated()` replaces `OnStart()`, `OnStopped()` or `OnDeactivated()` replace `OnSleep()`, and `OnResumed()` or `OnActivated()` replace `OnResume()`. I can implement this by creating a custom `Window` subclass and returning it from `CreateWindow()` in the `App` class.","outputTokens":1000,"requestId":"E830:2827DA:2542531:295560E:69F93FB5"},"id":"d5cae089-daea-48b8-847f-28f64fc60ddc","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:54:30.511Z","parentId":"569bc53f-3a6e-4a6f-8f59-54200100752a"}
